        hide-details></v-text-field>
    <v-data-table 
      v-model:search="search" 
      :items="msg?.payload" 
      :headers="msg?.headers"
      v-model="selected"
      item-selectable="selectable"
      select-strategy="all"
      show-select    
      return-object
    >

      <template v-slot:item.icon="{ item }">
        <v-icon :icon="item.icon"></v-icon>
      </template>

    </v-data-table>
</template>

<script>
    export default {
    data () {
      return {
        selected: [],
        search: ''
      }
    },
    watch: {
        selected: function () {
          this.send({topic:'selected', payload: this.selected});
        }
    },

  }
</script>

Text - Intro
content:
# Working with tables

Dashboard 2.0 (DB2) offers two different options to display tables, one is the `ui-table` component which can display any object array as a table, and has some customizibility on column headers.
But the real power is building tables using [Vuetify](https://vuetifyjs.com/en/components/data-tables/introduction/#components) `v-data-table` and the various Vuetify components to build reach and responsible tables.

name: Text - Header and Items
content: # Customizing Header and Items ## Linking items to the table In the `v-data-table` tag, `:items="msg.payload"` describes that the items to be displayed in the table are stored in `msg.payload` of the incoming message. ## Search It is possible to add a simple client side filter to the table values that filters on any column values in the table. First, it needs a search field `v-text-field` before (or after) the table: ``` ``` And also needs to be linked to the table using the `v-model:search="search"` attribute: ``` ``` ## Column headers By default the column headers are same as the field names with capital first letter. But it can be overriden to any text if needed: ``` ``` It needs a `template` tag with `v-slot` attribute, which says `header:xxx` where xxx is the field name. And within that the text can be defined. In the example above "Customer Satisfaction" in centre justified, otherwise it is left justified. ## Convert value to linked In the Email column an mailto: hyperlink is formatted, instead of the full email printed on the screen. ``` ``` Similar to the header changes, this also needs a `template` tag with `v-slot` attribute, which now says `item:xxx` where xxx is the field name. The value of `href` is calculated therefore it is shown as `:href` indicating that the value is not a text but an expression. ## Convert value to Chip Age is displayed as a chip, basically the value is cirled and shown with a background color. `{{ item.age }}` prints the age value and the work " years" is printed after it. ``` ``` The `color` attribute is determined my a function, so again it is referenced as `:color`. Function is defined in the methods section. ## Convert value to icon The "yes" and "no" value of the `ev` field is displayed as a green or red car icon. Both the color and the icon name is determined by a function. ``` ``` ## Convert value to rating A value from 1 to 5 can also be displayed as star rating. The rating being displated is passed in the `:model-value` attribute, and it takes the value from `item.rating`. ``` ``` ## Convert to Linear progress The `complete` field contains a value from 1 to 100 and that is shown as a progress. The progress value is passed in `:model-value` and the color is determined by a function. ``` ``` ## Script section ### data section In the data section only the `search` variable is defined which stores the search value entered in the input field and pass it over to the table to filter the results. ``` data () { return { search: '' } }, ``` ### methods section The methods section contains all the functions that are used by the chip, icon, progress components and determine color or icon for the component. The object for each record is stored in the `item` variable. I pass the entire `item` object to these functions, and they can reference to each field of it by `item.age`, `item.ev`, etc. And return either the color name, or icon name, etc.

content: # Temperature list The above table shows how the table can be used to display a list of value. Here a function code is updating some temperature readings randomly just to show that a continouse incoming payload refreshes the table contents. Also the search bar is turned off for this example. ## Adding buttons A plus and a minus button is added to the "Target Temperature" column to allow changing the value for each row: ``` ``` When either the plus or the minus button is pressed it will send the entire item in the payload and the topic will be either "plus" or "minus". Since there is an `id` field in the record, it will be easy to identify in which row the button is pressed. ## Linear progress The Current Temperature is shown as a "Linear Progress" similar as in the first example: ``` ``` But here the actual value is printed on top of the progress with the `{{ item.current }}°C` line. Also the color of the progress bar is determined by a function: `:color="getColor(item)"`. And this function is defined in the script section in methods: ``` methods: { // add a function to determine the color of the progress bar given the row's item getColor: function (item) { if (item.current > item.target) { return 'red' } else { return 'green' } } } ```
